{"id":"2302.09680","submitter":"Konstantin Donhauser","authors":"Konstantin Donhauser, Johan Lokna, Amartya Sanyal, March Boedihardjo,\n  Robert H\\\"onig, and Fanny Yang","title":"Sample-efficient private data release for Lipschitz functions under\n  sparsity assumptions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Differential privacy is the de facto standard for protecting privacy in a\nvariety of applications. One of the key challenges is private data release,\nwhich is particularly relevant in scenarios where limited information about the\ndesired statistics is available beforehand. Recent work has presented a\ndifferentially private data release algorithm that achieves optimal rates of\norder $n^{-1/d}$, with $n$ being the size of the dataset and $d$ being the\ndimension, for the worst-case error over all Lipschitz continuous statistics.\nThis type of guarantee is desirable in many practical applications, as for\ninstance it ensures that clusters present in the data are preserved. However,\ndue to the \"slow\" rates, it is often infeasible in practice unless the\ndimension of the data is small. We demonstrate that these rates can be\nsignificantly improved to $n^{-1/s}$ when only guarantees over s-sparse\nLipschitz continuous functions are required, or to $n^{-1/(s+1)}$ when the data\nlies on an unknown s-dimensional subspace, disregarding logarithmic factors. We\ntherefore obtain practically meaningful rates for moderate constants $s$ which\nmotivates future work on computationally efficient approximate algorithms for\nthis~problem.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 19 Feb 2023 22:00:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-21"}
