{"id":"2302.09957","submitter":"Ludovic Bellon","authors":"Salamb\\^o Dago, Sergio Ciliberto and Ludovic Bellon","title":"Adiabatic computing for optimal thermodynamic efficiency of information\n  processing","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Handling information in the physical world requires energy: Landauer's\nprinciple makes a strong connection between information theory and\nthermodynamics by stating that the erasure of a one-bit memory requires a work\nlarger than $W_{LB}=k_BT_0 \\ln2=3.10^{-21}\\,\\mathrm{J}$ at room temperature\n$T_0$, with $k_B$ Boltzmann's constant. This tiny limit has been experimentally\nillustrated, using quasi-static processes in model experiments. However when\ndecreasing the duration of operations, an energy overhead proportional to the\nprocessing speed appears. Bypassing this overhead for fast operations would be\na huge step towards efficient information processing. We show that underdamped\nsystems are the winning strategy to reduce this energetic cost. We prove both\nexperimentally and theoretically that, in the limit of vanishing dissipation\nmechanisms in the memory, the physical system is thermally insulated from its\nenvironment during fast erasures, i.e. fast protocols are adiabatic as no heat\nis exchanged with the bath. Using a fast optimal erasure protocol we also show\nthat these adiabatic processes produce a maximum adiabatic temperature\n$T_a=2T_0$, and that Landauer's bound for fast erasures in underdamped systems\nbecomes the adiabatic bound: $W_a = k_B T_0$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Feb 2023 13:01:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-21"}
